erNames>Mark</gtr:otherNames><gtr:surname>Wilson</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FE001661%2F1"><gtr:id>B6FF8645-4081-4C9D-8E90-479B2E2D18BD</gtr:id><gtr:title>Consumer Protection Policy and Competition</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/E001661/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>Despite the progress of economic theory, surprisingly little is known about the effects of deceptive advertising. The research will aim to deepen our theoretical understanding of such issues by analysing the conditions under which consumers may be willing to trust potentially false advertisements and how this may impact upon market competition and overall consumer welfare. The research will employ standard economic techniques alongside more modern behavioural approaches in order to offer more realistic insights into consumer behaviour and to provide better policy advice in how to best regulate advertising and market information.&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2008-09-14</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2006-10-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>152253</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:impactSummaryOutput><gtr:description>The findings from my papers have been cited in a number of UK and EU policy reports and publications.</gtr:description><gtr:firstYearOfImpact>2008</gtr:firstYearOfImpact><gtr:id>77CEA83F-E0F9-48A0-910E-0E17BA76BB9D</gtr:id><gtr:impactTypes><gtr:impactType>Economic,Policy &amp; public services</gtr:impactType></gtr:impactTypes><gtr:outcomeId>54647fa654f5f0.84456396</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sector>Energy</gtr:sector></gtr:impactSummaryOutput></gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>1. Consumers sometimes switch their supplier in markets like those such as energy. This is important because it provides competition and encourages suppliers to offer the cheapest prices and the best products. Many consumers don't do this however. Moreover, as my paper shows using data from the British energy market, that even the
consumers that do switch do it badly. Many consumers don't pick the best deal available and some consumers actually pick a deal that is worse than the one they were on already. We attribute this behaviour to consumer confusion. Policy should ensure that markets are clear and transparent to ensure this important consumer behaviour serves its competitive function properly.

2. If consumer are thinking about changing their supplier of a certain good, they often need to spend time and effort a) finding and understanding suppliers' prices and b) arranging the actual switch between suppliers. These activities can be quite tedious in some markets such as banking or energy. My research says that it time spent finding price information is the most important of the two in determining the prices in a market and in affecting consumers' welfare. Hence, policymakers should focus on improving consumers' information rather than making switching suppliers easier or quicker.

3. If consumers need to spend time finding out information to trade with a supplier, one might think that suppliers will have the incentive to help consumers by providing information through advertising or other means. However, my paper shows that suppliers sometimes have the incentive to do the opposite - by not advertising or even hiding information. By doing this they can disrupt competition in the market and increase their profits. Hence, this gives a role for policy to improve consumers' information to increase competition and raise consumers' welfare.</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>Further help policymaking.</gtr:exploitationPathways><gtr:id>81287640-6251-4940-931C-A9A58A8ADC47</gtr:id><gtr:outcomeId>546482116da361.43547130</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sectors><gtr:sector>Energy,Financial Services, and Management Consultancy,Government, Democracy and Justice,Retail</gtr:sector></gtr:sectors></gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>E1199DA9-12D5-4BE2-9907-3C6DDA933346</gtr:id><gtr:title>Ordered search and equilibrium obfuscation</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>International Journal of Industrial Organization</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/c690504953331fb806cb15021dc1c29b"><gtr:id>c690504953331fb806cb15021dc1c29b</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Wilson C</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2010-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:outcomeId>54647c3612ac88.93621497</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication><gtr:publication><gtr:id>CD6E23A1-51B3-43FC-A4F7-6E8A4E7B9668</gtr:id><gtr:title>Do consumers switch to the best supplier?</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Oxford Economic Papers</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/perso